astonish by a parade of knowledge<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="51"
                xml:id="pb-51"
                facs="#i51"/>
            <lb/>
49<lb/>
connected with indolence and knowledge<lb/>
is no less necessary in strengthening<lb/>
the mind than in preserving the<lb/>
purity of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">affections of the Heart</hi>
            <lb/>
Some few arguments are now<lb/>
and then brought forwards against<lb/>
the efficacy of popular instruction<lb/>
It is urged that superficial and<lb/>
general knowledge often tends to<lb/>
produce pedantry and that persons<lb/>
who are only learned are sometimes<lb/>
vain and presumptious -<lb/>
with regard to the charge of pedantry<lb/>
this can only be applied to <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the half</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">taught</hi> in manners as well as<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="52"
                xml:id="pb-52"
                facs="#i52"/>
            <lb/>
It offers new topics for conversation and<lb/>
new interests <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in life</hi>.<lb/>
In solitude it affords subjects for<lb/>
contemplation and for an active<lb/>
exercise of the understanding, and <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>on</unclear>
            </del>
            <lb/>
in cities it assists the cause of <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Religion</del>
            <lb/>
Religion and morality by <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">preventing</hi>
            <lb/>
the increase of gross luxury and<lb/>
indulgence in vicious <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dissipation</hi>-<lb/>
Man is designed for an active being<lb/>
And his spirit <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">ever restless</hi> if not<lb/>
employed upon worthy and dignified<lb/>
objects will often rather engage<lb/>
in mean and low pursuits <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
